        <body>       
                <pb n="1"/>
            <p>May 17 1890<lb/>
                1631 Chestnut St.<lb/>
                Philadelphia<lb/></p>
            <p>Dear Mr Morais&#45;<lb/></p>
            <p>I have been too poorly<lb/> to call and see you&#44; particularly<lb/> in reference to Charles Kohs be&#45;<lb/>havior at Mt Sinai Cemetery to<lb/> the Misses Phillips&#44; and other<lb/> members of their family&#45;&#45;As sexton<lb/> he has been instructed by the Presi&#45;<lb/>dent Mr. D. Teller to act courteously&#44;<lb/> and I would like a few lines from<lb/> you about his conduct on the oc&#45;<lb/>casion alluded to&#45;&#45;we have just<lb/> returned from a visit to Europe<lb/> where in <hi rend="underline">every</hi> locality I visited<lb/> our people and synagogues.  I<lb/> cannot express my feelings of sad&#45;<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="2"/>
            <p>&#45;ness at the dreadful condition<lb/> of our Russian co&#45;religionists.  Our<lb/> Minister Smith is <hi rend="underline">no friend</hi> of our<lb/> people a well established fact<lb/> in my mind long ago.  We should<lb/> be most glad to see you&#44; and trus&#45;<lb/>ting you are well.<lb/>  I remain Truly&#44;<lb/> Lucien Moss.<lb/></p>
            <p>I spent Thanksgiving day<lb/> sick in bed&#45;&#45;<lb/></p>
            </body>
    </text>
